<div class="header"><h1>Devices and Methods to Measure MSG and Disodium glutamate (DSG) (20251222)</h1></div>
<div class="body">
<p>
To measure the quantity of monosodium glutamate (MSG) and disodium guanylate
(often abbreviated DSG when referring to disodium glutamate, GMP) in a sample,
you generally need analytical chemistry instruments or specialized assays rather
than a simple consumer tester.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>1. Chromatography-Based Instruments (High Precision)</h2>

<p>
These are the gold-standard tools for quantifying specific food additives like
MSG and disodium guanylate.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC)</strong><br>
    Separates components in a sample and measures their concentration. With
    appropriate detectors (for example UV/Vis), HPLC provides accurate
    quantitative results for glutamate and guanylate compounds.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Liquid Chromatography–Mass Spectrometry (LC-MS / LC-MS/MS)</strong><br>
    Combines liquid chromatography with mass spectrometry for very sensitive and
    specific quantification, even in complex food matrices. Commonly used in
    research and regulatory food labs.
  </li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>2. Spectrophotometric / Colorimetric Assay Kits</h2>

<p>
These are simpler than full chromatography systems and are suitable for labs
without access to expensive instrumentation.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>L-Glutamic Acid (MSG) Enzymatic Assay Kits</strong><br>
    Use enzyme-driven reactions to quantify glutamate via a color change measured
    with a spectrophotometer or microplate reader.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>Glutamate Test Strips (Semi-Quantitative)</strong><br>
    Color-changing strips that estimate L-glutamate concentration. Useful for
    quick checks but not precise.
  </li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>3. Electronic Tongue Systems</h2>

<p>
Electronic tongues use arrays of cross-sensitive sensors to estimate taste
components, including umami contributors like MSG and guanylate.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    Useful for quality control and relative concentration comparisons.
  </li>
  <li>
    Not suitable for precise chemical quantification in mg/g or ppm.
  </li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>4. Other Laboratory Techniques</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>UV/Visible Spectrophotometry (after derivatization)</strong><br>
    Cost-effective method but less specific than chromatography.
  </li>
  <li>
    <strong>High-Performance Thin Layer Chromatography (HPTLC)</strong><br>
    Can be used for MSG under specialized protocols.
  </li>
</ul>

